04153nam a22005535i 9780520937314DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19991999cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209373147 a10.1525/97805209373142doi  a(DE-B1597)648012  a(OCoLC)1419789868  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0100002bisacsh1 aHeineman, Elizabeth D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhat Difference Does a Husband Make? :bWomen and Marital Status in Nazi and Postwar Germany /cElizabeth D. Heineman; ed. by Elizabeth D. Heineman. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1999] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b15 b/w photographs, 11 line illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies on the History of Society and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- t1. Introduction: War, Politics, and Marital Status -- t2. Housewives, Activists, and "Asocials" -- t3. War Wives, Workers, and Race Traitors -- t4. The Hour of the Women -- t5. Marriage Rubble -- t6. Restoring the Difference -- t7. Narrowing the Difference -- t8. What's the Difference? -- tEPILOGUE: Who's More Emancipated? -- tAppendix A: Statistics from Published Reports -- tAppendix B: The Darmstadt Study -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn October 1946, seven million more women than men lived in occupied Germany. In this study of unwed, divorced, widowed, and married women at work and at home across three political regimes, Elizabeth Heineman traces the transitions from early National Socialism through the war and on to the consolidation of democracy in the West and communism in the East.Based on thorough and extensive research in German national and regional archives as well as the archives of the U.S. occupying forces, this pathbreaking book argues that marital status can define women's position and experience as surely as race, gender, sexual orientation, and class. Heineman finds that, while the war made the experience of single women a dramatic one, state activity was equally important. As a result, West German women continued to be defined in large part by their marital status. In contrast, by the time of reunification marital status had become far less significant in the lives of East German women.In one broad, comprehensive sweep, Elizabeth Heineman compares prewar and postwar, East and West, lived experience and public policy. Her sharp analytical insights will enrich our understanding of the history of women in modern Germany and the role of marital status in twentieth-century life worldwide.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEurope. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh1 aHeineman, Elizabeth D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052023907440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093731440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520937314423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520937314/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles